# UV-Vis Beer-Lambert calibration — workshop scaffold

> **How to use this file.** This is a fill-in-the-blank scaffold, not a finished
> skill. Work through the milestones **in order** and complete each `TODO`. Do
> **not** skip ahead to baseline correction (M5). You are *meant* to hit a wall at
> M4 — that surprise is the whole lesson. Copy this file into your opencode skills
> directory (see the setup guide), drop the `.template` suffix, and refine the
> instructions until the agent does each step reliably.
>
> **Milestones:** M0 setup · M1 read peaks · M2 calibrate · M3 predict ·
> M4 benchmark (⚠ expect a shock) · M5 diagnose + correct + self-verify ·
> M6 hardening (fast track).

## What this skill does

When invoked, help the researcher quantify an unknown from UV-Vis calibration
data. The peak of interest is near **664 nm**. Data lives in a `data/` folder:

- `calibration_*.csv` — one spectrum per known standard (columns: `wavelength_nm,absorbance`)
- `calibration_index.csv` — maps each calibration filename to its known concentration (µM)
- `unknown.csv` — the sample to quantify (no concentration given)

Write and run small Python (numpy / scipy / matplotlib) to do the work. Show the
researcher your plots and numbers at each step.

